{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016n7TfNfQUNTv5mqiWTaDCz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The original ConfigMap:\n1. Uses `${POD_NAME}` for `node.name` - but wait, this gets stored literally in the ConfigMap (it's a `|` yaml block scalar). The ES startup script must be doing the substitution. Let me check the StatefulSet more carefully.\n\nActually, looking at the StatefulSet again - it mounts `elasticsearch.yml` directly from the ConfigMap, and `POD_NAME` is an env var. Elasticsearch 7.x supports environment variable substitution in config files using `${VAR_NAME}` syntax. So the original ConfigMap's `${POD_NAME}` gets substituted by ES at startup.\nThe broken ConfigMap has `node.name` as empty because the shell heredoc evaluated `${POD_NAME}` prematurely, and the `discovery.seed_hosts` points to the wrong domain. I need to restore the ConfigMap with the literal `${POD_NAME}` placeholder and correct seed hosts, then restart es-cluster-2 to pick up the changes. Since the ConfigMap is mounted with `subPath`, the pod will see the updated configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":697,"cache_read_input_tokens":34594,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":697},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6483a7ea-fae9-41bb-afcf-26ff534f4665","uuid":"241586a2-b697-4cad-9021-d6f8d0ccd4e2","request_id":"req_011CbyBxWTSwpWBy94diK4J7"}
